 Chapter 7 Bayesian Regression for Bounded and Skewed Continuous Outcomes in Stan In the previous posts, we worked through logistic regression for binary outcomes, negative binomial regression for overdispersed counts, and zero-inflated models for the structural excess of zeros. All of those dealt with discrete or binary outcomes. This post pivots to continuous outcomes, but with a twist: the distributions that govern them are neither Gaussian nor particularly well-behaved. Three workhorses emerge here — beta regression for proportions and rates bounded between 0 and 1, gamma regression for strictly positive right-skewed data, and the log-normal as a close cousin with slightly different theoretical commitments. Each one rewards a careful understanding before you reach for it. 7.1 Beta Regression: The Proportion Problem The most common mistake when modeling a proportion — say, the fraction of survey respondents who agree with a statement, or a student’s score as a share of the maximum — is to apply ordinary linear regression and hope for the best. The problem is not just that predictions can fall outside \([0, 1]\); it’s that variance in proportions is fundamentally heteroskedastic. Outcomes near 0.5 have more room to vary than outcomes near 0 or 1, which are squeezed against a boundary. A Gaussian model ignores this entirely. The beta distribution is parameterized, in its regression form, by a mean \(\mu \in (0, 1)\) and a precision parameter \(\phi &gt; 0\). The mean is modeled with a logit link, exactly as in logistic regression, but unlike logistic regression the outcome is a continuous value on the open interval rather than a binary indicator. The variance under this parameterization is: core.ac \[ 	ext{Var}(Y) =  rac{\mu(1 - \mu)}{\phi + 1} \] This makes the interpretation of \(\phi\) intuitive: larger values compress variance around the mean, and smaller values allow for more dispersion. You can also model \(\phi\) as a function of covariates — a so-called variable dispersion beta model — which is useful when the precision of responses changes systematically across groups. topmodels.r-forge.r-project One important boundary condition: the standard beta distribution is defined on the open interval \((0, 1)\), so exact zeros and ones are technically inadmissible. In practice this is handled either by a small transformation \((y(N-1) + 0.5)/N\) before modeling, or by switching to a zero-one inflated beta model when true boundary values are theoretically possible — a topic that parallels the zero-inflation machinery from the previous post quite directly. stat.ethz 7.2 Stan Implementation: Beta Regression The Stan model for beta regression is compact. The key is the beta_proportion_lpdf function, which takes the mean-precision parameterization directly, saving you from back-transforming to the \((\alpha,  eta)\) shape parameters manually. data { int&lt;lower=0&gt; N; int&lt;lower=0&gt; K; matrix[N, K] X; vector&lt;lower=0, upper=1&gt;[N] y; } parameters { vector[K] beta_mu; real&lt;lower=0&gt; phi; // precision } model { vector[N] mu = inv_logit(X * beta_mu); // Priors beta_mu [core.ac](https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/11055873.pdf) ~ normal(0, 5); for (k in 2:K) beta_mu[k] ~ normal(0, 2.5); phi ~ gamma(2, 0.1); // weakly informative; same logic as phi in ZINB for (n in 1:N) y[n] ~ beta_proportion(mu[n], phi); } generated quantities { vector[N] y_rep; for (n in 1:N) { real mu_n = inv_logit(dot_product(X[n], beta_mu)); y_rep[n] = beta_proportion_rng(mu_n, phi); } } The generated quantities block produces posterior predictive draws in the same \((0,1)\) range as the observed data, making it straightforward to run graphical posterior predictive checks — plot the density of y_rep against the observed y and look for systematic discrepancies near the boundaries or in the tails. andrewheiss Coefficient interpretation follows logistic regression convention. A coefficient \( eta_k\) on the logit scale translates to a multiplicative change in the odds of the mean: \(e^{ eta_k}\) is the odds ratio for \(\mu/(1-\mu)\). If you want the effect on the probability scale directly, compute the posterior distribution of \(	ext{inv\_logit}(\mathbf{X} oldsymbol{ eta})\) at meaningful covariate values rather than trying to apply a single additive summary. 7.3 Simulating Beta-Distributed Data in R Before fitting, it is worth understanding what beta regression data looks like in practice. library(tidyverse) library(rstan) set.seed(42) N &lt;- 3000 x1 &lt;- rnorm(N) x2 &lt;- runif(N, -2, 2) # True parameters alpha_true &lt;- -0.5 beta1_true &lt;- 0.8 beta2_true &lt;- -0.4 phi_true &lt;- 8 # moderate precision mu_true &lt;- plogis(alpha_true + beta1_true * x1 + beta2_true * x2) # Draw from beta using shape reparameterization a &lt;- mu_true * phi_true b &lt;- (1 - mu_true) * phi_true y &lt;- rbeta(N, a, b) df_beta &lt;- data.frame(y = y, x1 = x1, x2 = x2) cat(&quot;Mean of y:&quot;, round(mean(y), 3), &quot;
