u\)) plays a similar role to \(\phi\) in the negative binomial: larger values imply less dispersion relative to the mean, and the distribution approaches Gaussian as the shape grows large. math.cit.tum data { int&lt;lower=0&gt; N; int&lt;lower=0&gt; K; matrix[N, K] X; vector&lt;lower=0&gt;[N] y; } parameters { vector[K] beta_mu; real&lt;lower=0&gt; alpha_shape; // gamma shape } model { vector[N] mu = exp(X * beta_mu); beta_mu [core.ac](https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/11055873.pdf) ~ normal(0, 5); for (k in 2:K) beta_mu[k] ~ normal(0, 2.5); alpha_shape ~ gamma(2, 0.1); for (n in 1:N) y[n] ~ gamma(alpha_shape, alpha_shape / mu[n]); // mean = mu[n] } generated quantities { vector[N] y_rep; for (n in 1:N) { real mu_n = exp(dot_product(X[n], beta_mu)); y_rep[n] = gamma_rng(alpha_shape, alpha_shape / mu_n); } } The parameterization gamma(shape, rate) in Stan uses rate = shape / mu, which ensures the mean equals mu regardless of the shape. This is a common source of confusion when translating between R’s rgamma(shape, rate) and Stan — always double-check which parameterization your software uses. mc-stan 7.5 Log-Normal: A Different Philosophical Commitment The log-normal model covers essentially the same territory as gamma regression — strictly positive, right-skewed continuous outcomes — but makes a qualitatively different assumption. Rather than directly modeling the distribution of \(Y\), it asserts that \(\log(Y)\) is normally distributed with mean \(\mathbf{X} oldsymbol{ eta}\) and variance \(\sigma^2\). This is equivalent to saying the multiplicative random errors are lognormally distributed, which is natural in many biological and economic contexts where effects compound rather than add. repository.lppm.unila.ac In practice, the two models are often close. But the differences matter at the tails: the log-normal has heavier tails than the gamma for a given mean and variance, which makes it more forgiving of extreme observations. If your data has occasional very large outliers, the log-normal may fit better; if the distribution is closer to exponential in shape (thin right tail), gamma tends to be more appropriate. The empirical recommendation is to fit both and compare via LOO-ELPD, exactly as we did for ZIP versus ZINB in the previous post. home.iitk.ac The Stan implementation of log-normal is the simplest of the three: parameters { vector[K] beta_mu; real&lt;lower=0&gt; sigma; } model { beta_mu ~ normal(0, 2.5); sigma ~ exponential(1); y ~ lognormal(X * beta_mu, sigma); } One genuine advantage of the log-normal is interpretability: the coefficients \( oldsymbol{ eta}\) are directly the parameters of a normal model on the log scale, which many researchers find easier to communicate. A coefficient \( eta_k = 0.3\) means a one-unit increase in \(x_k\) shifts the median of \(Y\) by a factor of \(e^{0.3} \approx 1.35\). Note that this is a statement about the median, not the mean — the mean of a log-normal includes an additional \(e^{\sigma^2/2}\) inflation factor, which matters whenever \(\sigma\) is non-trivial. demonstrations.wolfram 7.6 Choosing Between Gamma and Log-Normal The following table summarizes the practical distinctions: Feature Gamma Log-Normal Variance structure \(	ext{Var}(Y) \propto \mu^2\) (constant CV) Increases faster than \(\mu^2\) in the tails Tail behavior Moderate right tail Heavier right tail Coefficients describe Multiplicative change in mean Multiplicative change in median Residuals on log scale Not normally distributed Normally distributed Common applications Insurance, reaction times, survival statisticsbyjim Income, gene expression, biological concentrations repository.lppm.unila.ac Stan family gamma(shape, shape/mu) lognormal(X*beta, sigma) Neither is universally superior. The gamma belongs to the exponential family and enjoys some convenient theoretical properties (GLM consistency, sufficient statistics), while the log-normal has the advantage that residual diagnostics on the log-transformed outcome are straightforward — you can literally plot log(y) - X*beta and assess normality. discourse.mc-stan 7.7 Posterior Predictive Checking: What to Look For The posterior predictive check strategy from the previous posts applies directly, but the diagnostics shift slightly for each family. For beta regression, the key check is whether the model reproduces the empirical density near the boundaries. If your outcome has many values above 0.9, a beta model with low precision may smear probability mass inappropriately toward 0.5. Plot the density of y_rep overlaid on observed y and pay particular attention to the tails. For gamma and log-normal, plot the log-scale residuals. Under a correctly specified gamma model, the Pearson residuals \((y - \hat\mu) / \hat\mu\) should be roughly constant in variance across the range of fitted values. Under a correctly specified log-normal, log(y) - X*beta should look Gaussian. Systematic fan-shaped patterns in either suggest the wrong variance function. The loo package comparison remains your quantitative arbiter when the graphical checks are ambiguous: discourse.mc-stan loo_compare(loo_gamma, loo_lognormal) A meaningful ELPD difference (larger than twice its standard error) favors one model; otherwise, both are defensible and theoretical motivation should guide the choice. 7.8 Practical Guidance A few lessons that get glossed over in textbook treatments: Beta regression strictly requires \((0,1)\) — exact zeros and ones will cause the log-likelihood to become unbounded. The simplest fix is the transformation \(	ilde y = (y(N-1) + 0.5)/N\), though if structural zeros or ones are theoretically meaningful, a zero-one-inflated beta model is more honest. stat.ethz Gamma regression can be sensitive to the shape prior. A gamma(2, 0.1) prior on the shape parameter is consistent with what we used for \(\phi\) in the ZINB, but if you expect very high dispersion (shape \(\approx 0.5\) or below) you may need a heavier-tailed prior like exponential(1) to avoid the sampler getting stuck near zero. The log-normal’s mean is not \(e^{\mathbf{X} oldsymbol{ eta}}\). The mean is \(e^{\mathbf{X} oldsymbol{ eta} + \sigma^2/2}\). If you’re computing marginal effects or making predictions on the original scale, this correction is non-negligible when \(\sigma &gt; 0.5\). All three models assume a continuous outcome with no mass at specific points. If your “proportion” data is actually \(k/n\) for small \(n\) (say, 3 successes out of 10), binomial or beta-binomial regression is more appropriate than beta regression, because the discreteness of the data-generating process matters. 7.9 References Ferrari, S., &amp; Cribari-Neto, F. (2004). Beta Regression for Modelling Rates and Proportions. Journal of Applied Statistics. ime.usp Stan Development Team. Stan Functions Reference mc-stan Cribari-Neto, F. &amp; Zeileis, A. (2010). Beta Regression in R. Journal of Statistical Software. topmodels.r-forge.r-project Vehtari, A., Gelman, A., &amp; Gabry, J. (2017). Practical Bayesian model evaluation using leave-one-out cross-validation and WAIC. Statistics and Computing. Stan Discourse: Comparing Gaussian, Gamma, and Lognormal regression discourse.mc-stan loo package documentation
